{{Infobox Christian denomination |name = Home of Truth |image = |alt = |imagewidth = 100px |caption = |main_classification = Home of Truth |orientation = [[New Thought]] |spiritual founder = [[Annie Rix Militz]], [[Harriet Hale Rix]] |founded_date = 1887 |founded_place = [[San Francisco, California]] |separated_from = |parent = |merger = |separations = |associations = [[Affiliated New Thought Network]], [[International New Thought Alliance]] |congregations = |members = |website = {{URL|http://thehomeoftruth.org/}} }}
{{NewThought}} The '''Home of Truth''' is a [[New Thought]] denomination founded in [[San Francisco, California]] founded by [[Annie Rix Militz]].<ref>[http://thehomeoftruth.org/id4.html "Our History"], The Home of Truth. Retrieved 12/11/11.</ref>
== History == In 1887, Annie Rix Milnz attended a class led by [[Emma Curtis Hopkins]] in her home city of San Francisco. Applying her [[metaphysics|metaphysical]] teachings, Rix cured her own chronic headaches and deafness in one ear. Soon after she founded a New Thought bureau with classes, a bookstore, and more. Rix soon married and started traveling the country; the San Francisco center was operated by her sister, Harriet Hale Rix.<ref>Keller, R.S., Ruether, R.R., Cantlon, M. (2006) ''Encyclopedia of women and religion in North America, Volume 1.'' Indiana University Press. p 760-761.</ref>
In the 1890s the bureau was renamed the "Home of Truth", and by 1903 there were eight Homes of Truth in the United States. The Homes of Truth attracted an almost exclusively female following.<ref>Satter, B. (2001) ''Each Mind a Kingdom: American Women, Sexual Purity, and the New Thought Movement, 1875-1920.'' University of California Press. p 103-105.</ref>
The denomination published ''[[Master Mind (magazine)|Master Mind]]'' magazine from 1911 to 1933.<ref>Dresser, H.W. (1919) ''A history of the new thought movement.'' T. Y. Crowell Company, 1919. p 232.</ref>
