{{Portal|Anglicanism}} The [[Right Reverend|Right Rev.]] ''' Charles Hope Gill '''  [[Master of Arts (Oxbridge and Dublin)|MA]], [[Doctor of Divinity|DD]] was [[Anglican Bishop of Travancore and Cochin|Bishop of Travancore and Cochin]] from 1905 to 1924.<ref>[http://anglicanhistory.org/india/chatterton1924/20.html Project Canterbury]</ref>

Gill was born into an ecclesiastical family <ref>He was the  son of the Reverend William Gill, sometime [[Rector (ecclesiastical)|Rector]] of [[Hertingfordbury]]  - "Who was Who" 1897-1990 London, A & C Black, 1991 {{ISBN|0-7136-3457-X}}</ref> on 11 February 1861 and educated at [[St Edmund's School|St Edmund’s School in Canterbury]], [[King William's College|King William’s College on the Isle of Man]] and [[Queens' College, Cambridge]]. He was [[ordained]] in 1865 <ref>''Ordinations.'' [[The Times]] (London, England), Tuesday,  2 June 1885; pg. 12; Issue 31462</ref> and began his career as a [[curate]] at St Peter’s, [[Tynemouth]]. Later he was a [[Church Mission Society|CMS]] [[Missionary]] at [[Shikarpur, Muzaffarnagar|Shikarpur]] and then  [[Jabalpur]]. From 1898 until his elevation to the [[Episcopate]] he was [[Church Mission Society|its]] [[Secretary]] in [[India]].<ref>"The Clergy List, Clerical Guide and Ecclesiastical Directory" London, John Phillips, 1900</ref>

On his return to [[Europe]] he was [[Vicar]] of [[Gerrard's Cross]] and then [[United Kingdom|British]] [[Chaplain]] at [[Hyères]]. He died on 29 June 1946.<ref>''Bishop C. Hope Gill.'' [[The Times]] (London, England), Monday,  1 Jul 1946; pg. 7; Issue 50491</ref>

