{{Orphan|date=February 2016}}

'''Thomas Baddy''' (died 1729) was an Independent minister and author.<ref name="DWB">{{cite web|title=Thomas Baddy|url=http://yba.llgc.org.uk/en/s-BADD-THO-1729.html|website=Dictionary of Welsh Biography|author=Robert Thomas Jenkins|year=1959|publisher=National Library of Wales|accessdate=23 February 2016}}</ref> 

==Early life and education==
Little is known about his family and early life, but he had a brother, Owen. He was described as being from Wrexham in 1690.<ref name="DWB" /> He studied in [[Rathmell]], [[Yorkshire]] at [[Richard Frankland (tutor)#Frankland's academy|Frankland's Academy]] beginning in 1689, and then at the [[Dissenting academies#Funding|Common Fund Board]] until 1693.<ref name="DWB" />

==Career==
He was a minister in [[Denbigh]] of the Independent congregation from 1693 until his death. During that time, he also filled in as needed at the Bala and Wrexham churches. Baddy was an author, translator, and wrote hymns, considered "the earliest known attempts at [[hymnody]] among Welsh Dissenters."<ref name="DWB" /> A series was published in 1703<ref name="Rees" /><ref>{{cite book|title=Y Cymmrodor: The Magazine of the Honourable Society of Cymmrodorion ...|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=4B9GAQAAMAAJ&pg=PA62|year=1883|publisher=The Society|page=62}}</ref> and ''Caniad Salomon'' was published in 1725.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://searchworks.stanford.edu/view/7975652 |title=Caniad Salomon|website=Stanford Libraries, Stanford University|accessdate=7 August 2017}}</ref> He translated ''Christian's Passover'' (''Pasc y Cristion'') and ''A Work by T. Wadswoth'' (1713) into Welsh.<ref name="Rees" />

==Personal life==
Baddy, who was well-off financially,<ref name="Rees">{{cite book|author=Thomas Mardy Rees|title=Notable Welshmen (1700-1900): ... with Brief Notes, in Chronological Order, and Authorities. Also a Complete Alphabetical Index|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=sXM_AQAAMAAJ&pg=PA29|year=1908|publisher=Herald Office|page=29–30, 73}}</ref> married Anne Salusbury of Galltfaenan, [[Denbighshire]] and they had a daughter who married a man with the surname Pugh<ref name="DWB" /> and another who married Rev. James Jardine, who was also an Independent minister in Denbigh.<ref name="Rees" /> He died in June 1729.<ref name="DWB" />

